<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>2 Samuel on Christian Internet Resources</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/</link><description>Recent content in 2 Samuel on Christian Internet Resources</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><atom:link href="https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>2 Samuel 1</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-01/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-01/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-1">2 Samuel Chapter 1&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="david-learns-of-sauls-death">David Learns of Saul’s Death&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>After Saul died, David came back from massacring the Amalekites and stayed two days in Ziklag. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>The third day, a man came from Saul’s camp with torn clothes and dust on his head. He prostrated himself to David. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:0in;'>&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>David said, &lt;i>“Where have you come from?”&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:0in;'>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>“I’ve escaped from Israel’s camp.”&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 2</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-02/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-02/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-2">2 Samuel Chapter 2&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="david-anointed-king-of-judah">David Anointed King of Judah&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="MsoSubtleReference">&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;/span>&lt;span class="MsoSubtleReference">&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%; font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;font-variant:normal !important;color:windowtext; text-decoration:none'>Afterwards David asked the &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>L&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>ORD&lt;/span>&lt;span class="MsoSubtleReference">&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%; font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;font-variant:normal !important;color:windowtext; text-decoration:none'>, &lt;i>“Should I go up to one of the towns in Judah?”&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="MsoSubtleReference">&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size: 12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;font-variant:normal !important; color:windowtext;text-decoration:none'>“Go on up.”&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="MsoSubtleReference">&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size: 12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;font-variant:normal !important; color:windowtext;text-decoration:none'>“Where?”&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="MsoSubtleReference">&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size: 12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;font-variant:normal !important; color:windowtext;text-decoration:none'>“To Hebron.”&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in;'>&lt;span class="MsoSubtleReference">&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%; font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;font-variant:normal !important;color:windowtext; text-decoration:none'>David and his two wives went there. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="MsoSubtleReference">&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;/span>&lt;span class="MsoSubtleReference">&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%; font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;font-variant:normal !important;color:windowtext; text-decoration:none'>He brought his men up with their families, and they lived in towns around Hebron. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="MsoSubtleReference">&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v4" id="v4">&lt;sup class="verse-num">4&lt;/sup> &lt;/span>&lt;span class="MsoSubtleReference">&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%; font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;font-variant:normal !important;color:windowtext; text-decoration:none'>Then the people in Judah came and anointed him king over Judah.&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 3</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-03/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-03/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-3">2 Samuel Chapter 3&lt;/h2>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>A long war had gone on between Saul and David. David had grown stronger; Saul had grown weaker. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size: 12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>David had &lt;i>six &lt;/i>sons in Hebron: Amnon his oldest by Ahinoam the Jezreelitess, &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Chileab second by Abigail, the widow of Nabal of Carmel; Absalom third by Maacah daughter of Tahmai, king of Geshur; &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v4" id="v4">&lt;sup class="verse-num">4&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> Adonijah fourth by Haggith, Shephatiah fifth by Abital, &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v5" id="v5">&lt;sup class="verse-num">5&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>and Ithream sixth by Eglah. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 4</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-04/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-04/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-4">2 Samuel Chapter 4&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="ish-bosheth-murdered">Ish-Bosheth Murdered&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>When Ish-bosheth heard that Abner had died in Hebron, his courage failed, and Israel lost courage too.
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Saul’s son had two men that were commanding raiding bands: Baanah and Rechab, sons of Rimmon, a Benjamite from Beeroth (&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>considered part of Benjamin). &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>The people of Beeroth fled to Gittaim and still live there as foreigners. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 5</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-05/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-05/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-5">2 Samuel Chapter 5&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="david-becomes-king-of-israel">David Becomes King of Israel&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in;'>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>            &lt;/span>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>All the tribes came to David in Hebron and said, &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in;margin-right:.5in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:.5in;'>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>“We’re your flesh and bones. &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>When Saul was king, you were the one that led Israel out and back. The &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>L&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>ORD&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> told you you’d shepherd his people.” &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in;'>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Israel’s elders came, and King David made a treaty with them in the &lt;i>L&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>ORD&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>’s&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> presence. They anointed him king over Israel. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v4" id="v4">&lt;sup class="verse-num">4&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>David was 30 and ruled for 40 years. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v5" id="v5">&lt;sup class="verse-num">5&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>He ruled Judah for 7½ years in Hebron and ruled Judah and Israel for 33 years in Jerusalem.  &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 6</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-06/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-06/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-6">2 Samuel Chapter 6&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="the-ark-brought-to-jerusalem">The Ark Brought to Jerusalem&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>David gathered elite troops from Israel again, 30,000. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>He and the troops went to Baale-judah to bring up God’s Ark called The Name: the L&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>ORD&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> of Hosts Enthroned Above the Cherubs.&lt;i> &lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>They placed the Ark on a new cart to bring it from Abinadab’s house that was on the hill. Uzzah and Ahio, Abinadab’s sons, &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v4" id="v4">&lt;sup class="verse-num">4&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>were bringing the Ark on the cart; Ahio was walking ahead of it. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v5" id="v5">&lt;sup class="verse-num">5&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Meanwhile, David and the House of Israel were celebrating enthusiastically in the L&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>ORD&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>’s presence with all kinds of instruments made out of fir: lyres, harps, tambourines, castanets, and cymbals. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 7</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-07/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-07/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-7">2 Samuel Chapter 7&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="gods-promise-to-david">God’s Promise to David&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>The king was living in his palace, and the L&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%; font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>ORD&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> had given him rest from his enemies. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size: 12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>He told Nathan the prophet, &lt;i>“I live in a cedar palace, but God’s Ark sits in tent curtains.” &lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:0in;'>&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Nathan said, &lt;i>“Do everything you’re thinking; the &lt;/i>&lt;i>L&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>ORD&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>’s with you.” &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 8</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-08/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-08/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-8">2 Samuel Chapter 8&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="davids-victories">David’s Victories&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:0in;'>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>After that, David defeated the Philistines and took Methegammah. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size: 12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>He defeated Moab and counted them off in lines and made them lie down on the ground. Two lines he counted off to be put to death, and one line he let live. The Moabites served him and brought tribute.&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size: 12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>David also defeated Hadadezer son of Rehob, king of Zobah, as he went to restore his power at the &lt;i>Euphrates&lt;/i> River. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v4" id="v4">&lt;sup class="verse-num">4&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>He took 1,700 cavalry and 20,000 infantry. He hamstrung the chariot horses but left enough for 100 chariots. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 9</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-09/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-09/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-9">2 Samuel Chapter 9&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="davids-kindness-to-mephibosheth">David’s Kindness to Mephibosheth&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Then David asked if anybody was left from Saul’s house that he could show kindness out of regard for Jonathan&lt;i>.&lt;/i> &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size: 12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>There was a servant named Ziba. They called him to David, and the king said, &lt;i>“You are Ziba?”
&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:0in;'>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>“I’m your servant.” &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:0in;'>&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>“Is anybody left in Saul’s family I can show God’s kindness?” &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 10</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-10/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-10/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-10">2 Samuel Chapter 10&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="david-defeats-the-ammonites">David Defeats the Ammonites&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>The king of the Ammonites died, and &lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>his son &lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Hanun became king. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size: 12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>David said, &lt;i>“I’ll be kind to Hanun son of Nahash like his father was kind to me.” &lt;/i>David sent some ambassadors to console him about his father. But when they got there, &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>the Ammonite officials said to Hanun, &lt;i>“Do you think David is honoring your father because he sent consolers? Hasn’t he sent them to look over the city, spy it out, and overthrow it?”&lt;/i> &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v4" id="v4">&lt;sup class="verse-num">4&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Hanun took David’s ambassadors and shaved off half their beards, cut off their cloaks as high as their hips, and sent them away. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v5" id="v5">&lt;sup class="verse-num">5&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>When David found out, he sent to meet them because they were really humiliated. He told &lt;i>them&lt;/i> to stay at Jericho till their beards grew, and then come back.&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 11</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-11/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-11/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-11">2 Samuel Chapter 11&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="david-and-bathsheba">David and Bathsheba&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>In the spring when kings normally go to war, David sent Joab and Israel’s army to destroy the Ammonites and lay siege to Rabbah. David stayed in Jerusalem.&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size: 12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>When evening came, David got up from his bed and walked around on the roof of his palace. From the roof he saw a woman taking a bath; she was beautiful. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>David sent and asked about her. Someone said, &lt;i>“Isn’t this Bathsheba, daughter of Eliam, wife of Uriah the Hittite?” &lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v4" id="v4">&lt;sup class="verse-num">4&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>David sent messengers and took her. When she came to him, he slept with her. When she’d purified herself, she went home. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v5" id="v5">&lt;sup class="verse-num">5&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>She got pregnant and sent and told David.&lt;b>                                                                                                                       &lt;/b>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 12</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-12/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-12/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-12">2 Samuel Chapter 12&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="nathan-rebukes-david">Nathan Rebukes David&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Then the L&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>ORD&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> sent Nathan to David to say,&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in;margin-right:.5in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:.5in;'>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>“Two men were in a town, one rich, the other poor. &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>The rich man had lots of flocks and herds, &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>but the poor man had nothing but one little ewe lamb that he’d bought and raised. It grew up with him and his children; it used to eat his bread and drink from his cup and lie in his lap; it was like a daughter to him. &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v4" id="v4">&lt;sup class="verse-num">4&lt;/sup> &lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>A traveler came to the rich man, and he wasn’t willing to take one of his own flock or herd to fix&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%; font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> a meal&lt;i> for him. He took the poor man’s lamb and fixed it.”&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 13</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-13/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-13/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-13">2 Samuel Chapter 13&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="amnon-and-tamar">Amnon and Tamar&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>David’s son Absalom had a beautiful sister named Tamar, and David’s son Ammon was in love with her. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Amnon was so frustrated because of his sister that he made himself ill, because she was a virgin and it seemed hard to do anything to her. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>But Amnon had a friend Jonadab son of Shimeah, David’s brother, and Jonadab was a shrewd fellow. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 14</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-14/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-14/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-14">2 Samuel Chapter 14&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="absalom-returns-to-jerusalem">Absalom Returns to Jerusalem&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:0in;'>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Joab sensed that the king yearned for Absalom. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>So he sent to Tekoa and brought a wise woman, and told her, &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in;margin-right:.5in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:.5in;'>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>“Act like you’re in mourning. Put on mourning clothes, don’t anoint yourself with oil. &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family: "Times New Roman",serif'>Act &lt;i>like a woman that’s been mourning for the dead for many days&lt;/i>. &lt;/span>&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Then go to the king and say such and such.”&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 15</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-15/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-15/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-15">2 Samuel Chapter 15&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="absaloms-conspiracy">Absalom’s Conspiracy&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>After that, Absalom provided himself a chariot, horses, and 50 men to run ahead of him. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>He’d get up early and stand by the road to the gate. When anybody had a suit to come to the king for judgment, Absalom would call to him and say, &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:0in;'>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>“What city are you from?” &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:0in;'>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>He’d say, &lt;i>“I’m from a tribe in Israel.”&lt;/i> &lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 16</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-16/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-16/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-16">2 Samuel Chapter 16&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="david-and-ziba">David and Ziba&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>When David had gone a little past the summit, Ziba, Mephibosheth’s steward, met him with a couple saddled donkeys. They were carrying 200 loaves of bread, 100 clusters of raisins, 100 summer fruits, and a skin of wine. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:0in;'>&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>The king asked, &lt;i>“Why do you have these?” &lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family: "Times New Roman",serif'>“The donkeys are for the king’s family to ride. The bread and summer fruit are for the young men to eat. The wine is for anybody to drink that’s become exhausted in the country.”&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> &lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 17</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-17/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-17/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-17">2 Samuel Chapter 17&lt;/h2>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>In addition, Ahithophel told Absalom, &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in;margin-right:.5in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:.5in;'>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>“Let me choose 12,000 men to pursue David tonight. &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>I’ll attack him while he’s exhausted and terrify him. The people with him will run. I’ll only strike down the king &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>and bring the people back to you. Everybody’s return depends on the man you’re looking for. Then the people will be at peace.”&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 18</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-18/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-18/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-18">2 Samuel Chapter 18&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="the-death-of-absalom">The Death of Absalom&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Then David counted his people and set over them commanders of thousands and hundreds. &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>He sent out the troops, a third each under Joab, Abishai, and Ittai. He told them,
&lt;i>“I’ll go out with you too.” &lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family: "Times New Roman",serif'> &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>They said, &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-top:0in;margin-right:.5in; margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:.5in;'>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>“You shouldn’t go out. If we flee, they won’t care even if half of us die. You’re worth 10,000 of us. It’s better for you to be ready to help us from town.” &lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 19</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-19/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-19/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-19">2 Samuel Chapter 19&lt;/h2>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in;'>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>            &lt;/span>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>Then Joab heard, &lt;i>“The king is crying and mourning for Absalom.”&lt;/i> &lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>The victory that day turned into mourning because those who heard about it said, &lt;i>“The king is grieving for his son.” &lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v3" id="v3">&lt;sup class="verse-num">3&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>So the people slipped into the city like humiliated people sneak away from battle.
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v4" id="v4">&lt;sup class="verse-num">4&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>The king covered his face and cried out, &lt;i>“Absalom! My son! My son!”&lt;/i> &lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 20</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-20/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-20/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-20">2 Samuel Chapter 20&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="sheba-rebels-against-david">Sheba Rebels Against David&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>A troublemaker happened to be there—Sheba son of Bicri, a Benjamite. He blew the ram’s horn and said,&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family: "Times New Roman",serif'>            &lt;a name="_Hlk91690564">&lt;i>“We don’t have any part with David&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family: "Times New Roman",serif'>                        or any inheritance in Jesse’s son.&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family: "Times New Roman",serif'>            Everybody, go home, Israel!”&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in;'>&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>The men from Israel deserted David and followed Sheba. But Judah stayed firmly committed to their king &lt;i>and escorted him &lt;/i>from the Jordan to Jerusalem.&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 21</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-21/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-21/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-21">2 Samuel Chapter 21&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="david-avenges-the-gibeonites">David Avenges the Gibeonites&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;span class="verse verse-v1" id="v1">&lt;sup class="verse-num">1&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>In David’s time, a famine came that lasted three years. He sought the L&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size: 9.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>ORD&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>. The L&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>ORD&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> said, &lt;i>“It’s because Saul and his bloody family murdered the people in Gibeon.” &lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;span style='font-size: 12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> (&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>The inhabitants of Gibeon weren’t part of Israel but a remnant of the Amorites. The Israelites had made a treaty with them, but Saul had intended to kill them off in his zeal for Israel and Judah&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>.) The king called them,&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 Samuel 22</title><link>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-22/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/translations/cnt-ot/2-samuel/chapter-22/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="2-samuel-chapter-22">2 Samuel Chapter 22&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="davids-song-of-praise-psalm-22">David’s Song of Praise (Psalm 22)&lt;/h3>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in;'>&lt;b>&lt;span style='font-size:14.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>         22&lt;sup>:1&lt;/sup>&lt;/span>&lt;/b>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>David sang this song to the L&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%; font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>ORD&lt;/span>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> when he delivered him from his enemies and from Saul:&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class="MsoListBulletCxSpMiddle" style='margin-bottom:0in; '>&lt;a name="_Hlk113353165">&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>            &lt;/span>&lt;/a>&lt;span class="verse verse-v2" id="v2">&lt;sup class="verse-num">2&lt;/sup> &lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>“The
&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>L&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>ORD&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;i>&lt;span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'> is my rock, my fortress, my deliverer,&lt;/span>&lt;/i>&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
